{"ts": "2026-06-07T23:06:56.330555+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Here's the full walkthrough. There are **six migrations** recorded in this repository. Three of them have SQL files currently checked into the `migrations/` directory; the other three have been applied in deployed environments but their files have been archived out of the working tree. The authoritative record is `MIGRATION_HISTORY.md`.\n\n---\n\n## Migrations in application order\n\n### 1. `001_create_users.sql` (2024-11-04) ✅ file present\n\nCreates the foundational **`users`** table:\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE users (\n    id           BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n    email        TEXT UNIQUE NOT NULL,\n    display_name TEXT,\n    created_at   TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now()\n);\n```\n\n- **`id`**: auto-incrementing 64-bit integer primary key.\n- **`email`**: unique, not-null text — the natural key for login.\n- **`display_name`**: nullable free-text display name.\n- **`created_at`**: timestamptz with a default of `now()`.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `002_create_sessions.sql` (2024-12-10) ✅ file present\n\nCreates the **`sessions`** table with a foreign key back to `users`:\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE sessions (\n    id          UUID PRIMARY KEY,\n    user_id     BIGINT NOT NULL REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n    issued_at   TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now(),\n    expires_at  TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL\n);\n```\n\n- **`id`**: UUID primary key (good for session tokens — non-sequential, hard to guess).\n- **`user_id`**: FK to `users(id)` with `ON DELETE CASCADE`, so deleting a user automatically purges their sessions.\n- **`issued_at` / `expires_at`**: define the session lifetime window.\n\n---\n\n### 3. `003_add_session_index.sql` (2025-01-22) ✅ file present\n\nAdds a **B-tree index** on `sessions.user_id`:\n\n```sql\nCREATE INDEX idx_sessions_user_id ON sessions(user_id);\n```\n\nSpeeds up the most common query pattern: \"look up all active sessions for a given user.\" Without this, every such query would do a full table scan.\n\n---\n\n### 4. `004_partition_users.sql` (2025-02-18) 🗄️ file archived\n\nConverts the **`users`** table to **range-partition by `created_at` on a monthly cadence**. (The SQL file has been archived out of the working tree, so the exact DDL isn't inspectable here, but the history notes describe it.) This is a common scalability move — monthly partitions let you prune old data or index only recent partitions.\n\n---\n\n### 5. `005_archive_legacy_sessions.sql` (2025-03-05) 🗄️ file archived\n\nMoves sessions older than **90 days** into a **`sessions_archive`** table. This keeps the hot `sessions` table small and fast while preserving old records for audit or analytics.\n\n---\n\n### 6. `006_grant_readonly_role.sql` (2025-04-12) 🗄️ file archived\n\nCreates an **`app_readonly`** database role and grants it read-only (`SELECT`) permissions on the relevant tables. This is the security boundary — application read replicas or analytics tools connect with this least-privilege role instead of the full owner account.\n\n---\n\n## Key things to know as you pick up this repo\n\n| Topic | Detail |\n|---|---|\n| **Engine** | PostgreSQL (evidenced by `BIGSERIAL`, `TIMESTAMPTZ`, `UUID` PKs, `CREATE INDEX` syntax, and `docker-compose.yml` likely running Postgres). |\n| **Migrations 004–006 are missing from the tree** | Their SQL files were archived after being applied. `MIGRATION_HISTORY.md` is the source of truth for what has run in each environment. |\n| **Naming convention** | `NNN_description.sql` — simple sequential numbering, no ORM-specific migration tool. |\n| **Schema shape after all 6** | `users` (monthly-partitioned) → `sessions` (hot) + `sessions_archive` (cold), plus an `app_readonly` role with SELECT grants. |\n\nLet me know if you'd like to dig into any of the other directories (config, scripts, seeds, docs) or need help modifying any of the migrations.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_met